      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Attorney. PENSION U APR 12 1883 OFFICE Adjutant General's Office Washington, D.C. October 7th, 1867 Sir: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt from your Office of application for Pension No. 152714, and to return it herewith, with such information as is furnished by the files of this Office. It appears from the Rolls on file in this Office, that Aaron Chamber was enrolled on the 19th day of Sept., 1861, at Owensboro, Ky., in Co. \"G\" 118th Regiment of U.S. Col. Infty Volunteers, to serve three years, or during the war, and mustered into service as a Private on the 19th day of Sept., 1861, at Owensboro, Ky., in Co. \"G\" 118th Regiment of U.S. Col. Infty Volunteers, to serve three years, or during the war. On the Muster Roll of Co. \"G\" of that Regiment, dated Hides Rendezvous, 2nd, 6th, 1862, he is reported \"Recd. of disease in field Hospital Co. No. 6/61.\" I am, Sir, very respectfully, Your obedient servant, E. W. Taggart The Commissioner of Pensions Washington, D.C. Assistant Adjutant General and Lieut. U.S. Army In charge of Pension Act. of hospital",
