    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "We, John Dixon, of lawful age, a resident of the (1) County of Richmond, in the State of Kentucky, at James Sutton, of lawful age, a resident of the (1) County of Richmond, in the State of Kentucky, upon our claim, jointly declare that he was personally well acquainted with Mrs. Kean Chambers, widow of (1) Aaron Chambers, now deceased, and was not sent to Private in Company E, commanded by Captain Moore, in the 1818 Regiment of (2) United States Colored Volunteers, commanded by Colonel Moore, in the war of 1776-1778. We further declare that we were likewise personally well acquainted with the said (1) Aaron Chambers, deceased, and his said wife, the said Mrs. Kean Chambers, during the lifetime of the former, and know that they lived and exhibited together as husband and wife for the period at least of (2) Twenty years prior to his death, which length of time in the longest period of cohabitation, known to us. That said parties were reported as husband and wife, and that we never heard a question raised or a doubt concerned to the contrary as to their being such. Furthermore, we have often heard the said (1) Aaron Chambers call the said Mrs. Kean Chambers \"wife,\" and always heard him speak of, and know that he ever treated and suspected her as such relation. We also state that she is esteemed and known as a respectable woman in the community of her residence. We further declare that at the time of service, we resided in the army, established, County and State with the deceased soldier, and know that he, the said (1) Aaron Chambers, previous to his entering the said service of the United States, was a man of good sound physical health. Our knowledge of said soldier's physical condition prior to enlistment, as above stated, is finished upon several observations and intimate acquaintance with him and not heard upon information derived from others, nor upon general reason. That he died (1) While in the service aforesaid in the (1) United States, in the State of Virginia on or about the Sixth day of November A.D. 1864, from the effects of (2) Wounds, described in the service of the United States, and as we verily believe from general reports, and without the slightest doubt to the contrary, while in the line of his duty therein. That Mrs. Kean Chambers, his widow aforesaid, applying for Army Pension by reason of the above named military service, is now a widow, and has remained such ever since the death of her said husband, the said (1) Aaron Chambers, above mentioned. That we make this affidavit as a simple act of justice to the applicant, and for an other purpose, having an interest in so doing whatsoever. That we fully understand the import and meaning of all the facts embodied in this affidavit, and to which we freely testify.",
